						<summary>

						<p>Pāṇikēśvarasvāmin temple. On a pillar in the <hi rend="italic">mukha-maṇḍapa.</hi></p>						

						<l n="28:142:85:0"><ta>••• ••• ••• •••</ta></l>						

						<p>There are four labels one below the other in different languages and scripts.</p>						

						<p>On top is one in Kannaḍa language and Telugu-Kannaḍa characters of about the 8th century A.D., which reads:</p>						

						<l n="28:142:85:1"><katr>Dēvara-bāyin-vōḻiḻdon-Pa-</katr></l>						

						<l n="28:142:85:2"><katr>[ḷḷa]-paḍiyāran</katr></l>						

						<p>The second one in Telugu characters (late) records the obeisance of [Vi]bhūti-Gauraya. </p>						

						<p>The third one is a repeat of the one in Telugu characters, in Nāgarī (late)</p>						

						<p>The fourth one in late Tamil characters records the same as above but translates <hi rend="italic">vibhūti</hi> as <hi rend="italic">tiruvaṇīṟu.</hi></p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
